            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/21050",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=wil",
                        "name": "wil",
                        "displayName": "Wil Sinclair",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This doesn't appear to have been fixed in 1.5.0. Please update if this is not correct.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=wil",
                        "name": "wil",
                        "displayName": "Wil Sinclair",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-04-18T13:12:04.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-04-18T13:12:04.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/37033",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=cwt137",
                        "name": "cwt137",
                        "displayName": "Christopher Thomas",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I'm willing to work on this, but there is only one solution I can think of. It is easy to sync the properties and metadata when the developer calls setMetadata(), but there is no setProperties() method. This prevents syncing when the properties is updated. I think the solution is to make the properties attribute protected and then create a getter and setter for it. Then the developer is forced to use the setProperties() method and this will ensure the metadata will be synced. The only problem with this solution is that it changes the API. How do you feel about this Alex?\r\n\r\nI thought of just doing the syncing when the pdf is being rendered\/saved, but decided it was not a good idea. For example, there might be the title \"foo\" in the properties and the title \"bar\" in the metadata. Which way do you sync? This is why I thought the API change way is the way to implement this feature.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=cwt137",
                        "name": "cwt137",
                        "displayName": "Christopher Thomas",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-12-18T06:19:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-12-18T06:19:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/37040",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=alexander",
                        "name": "alexander",
                        "displayName": "Alexander Veremyev",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "It's possible to use ArrayObject to intercept array elements update.\r\n\r\n{code}\r\nclass MyCoolArray extends ArrayObject {\r\n    public function offsetSet($index, $newval) {\r\n        printf(\"Set operation: array[%s] = '%s'\\n\", $index, $newval);\r\n\r\n        parent::offsetSet($index, $newval);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n$a = new MyCoolArray();\r\n$a[5] = 'some_value';\r\n{code}\r\nproduces\r\n{panel}\r\nSet operation: array[5] = 'some_value'\r\n{panel}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=alexander",
                        "name": "alexander",
                        "displayName": "Alexander Veremyev",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-12-18T07:39:31.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-12-18T07:40:31.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
